{"id":"math-ph/0306016","submitter":"Justin Abbott","authors":"J. Abbott","title":"Low Temperature Results for the Heisenberg XXZ and XY Models","comments":"Ph.D. Thesis, 77 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math-ph math.MP","license":null,"abstract":"  This thesis contains two results for the low temperature behavior of quantum\nspin systems. First, we present a lower bound for the spin-1 XXZ chain in\nfinite volumes in terms of the gap of the two-site Hamiltonian. The estimate is\nderived by a method developed by Nachtergaele in (cond-mat/9410110) called the\nMartingale Method. Our bound relies on an assumption which we have, as yet,\nbeen unable to verify analytically in all cases. We present numerical evidence\nthat strongly indicates our assumption is valid.\n  The second result is a proof that the spin-1/2, d-dimensional XY model in the\npresence of an external magnetic field does not undergo a phase transition at\nlow temperature, provided that the strength of the field is great enough. Using\na contour expansion inspired by Kennedy, we show that the weights of contours\nsatisfy a condition of Kotecky and Preiss which allows us to express the free\nenergy of the system as a cluster expansion. As part of the setup we give a\nsimple proof that the all-spin-up state is the unique ground state when the\nexternal magnetic field has strength at least 2d.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 5 Jun 2003 00:15:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
